Purpose

This document summarizes the current state of Phase 3 after the closure of:

Phase 3 Wave 1
Phase 3 Wave 2 lightweight adapter pack

It records:

why Phase 3 was opened
what Phase 3 has actually delivered so far
how Wave 1 and Wave 2 relate to each other
what product meaning Phase 3 now has in TraceFold
what boundaries have remained preserved
what remains intentionally undecided or outside current closure
what kinds of next-step directions are reasonable after this point

This document does not claim full Phase 3 completion.
It records the current bounded state of Phase 3 after two completed waves.

Project Position

TraceFold remains:

a local-first personal data workbench / personal data platform
centered on the main chain
Capture -> Parse -> Pending -> Confirm -> Formal Record -> Query / Analysis / Derivation
centered on the application service layer as the only business-logic center
centered on SQLite as the single source of truth
centered on Web as the main business interface
with Desktop as shell-level entry
with Telegram as lightweight adapter
with Feishu now also established as a lightweight adapter within bounded scope

Phase 1 is complete and closed.
Post-Phase-1 Web main consumption-line optimization is closed.
Phase 2 V1 bounded closure is closed.
Post-Phase-2 bounded bilingual Web UI support is closed.

Phase 3 therefore began from a sufficiently stable product and architecture baseline.

Why Phase 3 Was Opened

Phase 3 was not opened to expand AI, graphization, automation, or multi-surface platformization.

It was opened because the next major user-facing weakness had become clear:

the system had become more usable, but daily repeated use still did not feel smooth enough.

In practice, this problem appeared in several connected ways:

quick single-item input still felt too deliberate
larger-volume input still lacked a bounded practical intake path
easier input needed better upstream triage rather than just more records
detail/readback surfaces still needed more coherent hierarchy and density for repeated use
after Web-side intake improvements, message-based entry surfaces became the next natural friction point

So Phase 3 became a stage centered on:

improving daily-use usability while preserving the same main chain, the same service-centered architecture, and the same formal-first downstream model.

High-Level Meaning of Phase 3 So Far

At this point, Phase 3 should be understood as having improved two things together:

how information gets into the system
how information is read back and resumed in use

Wave 1 focused primarily on improving intake and readback inside the current workbench/Web surfaces.

Wave 2 extended low-friction intake outward into lightweight chat-based adapters, while still preserving the same capture-first contract.

Together, these waves make TraceFold materially more like a system that can be used repeatedly in ordinary life rather than only as a structurally correct but more deliberate workbench.

